01:18:53.000 --> 01:18:59.000
And meanwhile, what he had done, he was using, and something he thought of,

01:18:59.000 --> 01:19:02.000
made it clear he had thought of it this time past.

01:19:02.000 --> 01:19:09.000
Peace bonds, where they get people to swear out complaints and have bonds issued,

01:19:09.000 --> 01:19:15.000
where then you have to put up property in order to be released from custody.

01:19:15.000 --> 01:19:20.000
To what I was doing or others like me are doing is disturbing their peace.

01:19:20.000 --> 01:19:22.000
It's not a disturbing the peace charge.

01:19:22.000 --> 01:19:26.000
It's disturbing the peace enough so that a peace bond is issued.

01:19:26.000 --> 01:19:29.000
They used to be used in domestic disputes and one kind or another.

01:19:29.000 --> 01:19:33.000
And what he did is he put on bail terms that were very onerous.

01:19:33.000 --> 01:19:37.000
And I think about it for a minute. Savannah is a city of about what, 200, 300,000.

01:19:37.000 --> 01:19:40.000
And he would stack the charges for stack.

01:19:40.000 --> 01:19:42.000
So I had seven peace bonds for him.

01:19:42.000 --> 01:19:45.000
He was saying, Hosea Williams had seven or eight and so on.

01:19:45.000 --> 01:19:50.000
Each one he required unencumbered property.

01:19:50.000 --> 01:19:52.000
And you just didn't have enough.

01:19:52.000 --> 01:19:53.000
Right.

01:19:53.000 --> 01:19:59.000
And so what you de facto had done was 49 or 49 or 45 or 50 people.

01:19:59.000 --> 01:20:03.000
And then someone would be let out, and I'll say be let out, then they put them back in.

01:20:03.000 --> 01:20:04.000
I'd pick the charges again.

01:20:04.000 --> 01:20:11.000
Anyway, what I recall is that the gentleman who was the one who was in court who gave testimony

01:20:11.000 --> 01:20:19.000
that I had disturbed his peace, he himself was an older gentleman and couldn't identify me in the courtroom.

01:20:19.000 --> 01:20:21.000
Plus I had not been there.

01:20:21.000 --> 01:20:25.000
But even across the courtroom and so on and so forth.

01:20:25.000 --> 01:20:31.000
Anyway, so I go back in later Ronald Goldfarb,

01:20:31.000 --> 01:20:42.000
who's made something of a reputation for himself years ago as expert on bail and preventive detention and this sort of thing.

01:20:42.000 --> 01:20:50.000
That fall was lecturing at the Yale Law School and a friend of mine, Peter Dibwad, who had gone to Wesleyan acquaintance of mine,

01:20:50.000 --> 01:21:01.000
as he put it dozing in the back and Ronald Goldfarb is discussing onerous bail by cases.

01:21:01.000 --> 01:21:08.000
Peter describes that he woke up to the fact that my name is mentioned as part of this case.

01:21:08.000 --> 01:21:15.000
Well, they kept me for a while in the solitary.

